  Patricia Lee "Patti" Smith (born December 30, 1946) is an American 

singer-songwriter, poet and visual artist, who became a highly 

influential component of the New York City punk rock movement with her 

1975 debut album Horses

  Called the "Godmother of Punk",her work was a fusion of rock and 

poetry. Smith's most widely known song is "Because the Night", which was 

co-written with Bruce Springsteen and reached number 13 on the Billboard 

Hot 100 chart in 1978.In 2005, Patti Smith was named a Commander of the 

Ordre des Arts et des Lettres by the French Ministry of Culture and in 

2007, she was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.On November 

17, 2010, she won the National Book Award for her memoir Just Kids.She 

is also a recipient of the 2011 Polar Music Prize.
